1.
Visit DigitalOcean.com and create an account.
https://www.digitalocean.com
[ or https://www.digitalocean.com/?refcode=f1f3befc8e75 if you want to give me some referral points which are always welcome :) ]

2.
Create a "Droplet" - your SSD VPS
Assign a hostname, pick a size, select a region, and choose your Linux distro.
CENTOS 6.4 X64 512 MB / 1 CPU / 20GB SSD DISK, 1TB TRANSFER = $5 PER MONTH

3.
Use puTTy or kiTTy to connect to your new server
It literally takes less than a minute for your new server to be spun up. DigitalOcean will email you the IP Address and root password when it is ready.
yum update
yum install wget
Install JAVA
https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-install-java-on-centos-and-fedora

sudo wget --no-cookies --no-check-certificate --header "Cookie: gpw_e24=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.oracle.com%2F; oraclelicense=accept-securebackup-cookie" \
"http://download.oracle.com/otn-pub/java/jdk/8u25-b17/jre-8u25-linux-x64.tar.gz"

sudo tar xvf jre-8u25-linux-x64.tar.gz
sudo chown -R root: jre1.8.0_25
sudo alternatives --install /usr/bin/java java /opt/jre1.8.0_25/bin/java 1
sudo rm /opt/jre-8u25-linux-x64.tar.gz

set java home
export JAVA_HOME=/opt/jre1.8.0_25

4.
Update, Download and Extract

cd /tmp/
I Skipped
wget http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/downloads/binary/atlassian-confluence-5.5.3-x64.bin

wget http://www.atlassian.com/software/jira/downloads/binary/atlassian-jira-6.3.13-x64.bin
wget http://dev.mysql.com/get/Downloads/Connector-J/mysql-connector-java-5.1.34.tar.gz
tar -xvzf mysql-connector-java-5.1.34.tar.gz
chmod +x *.bin


5.
Install MySQL
see this
https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-install-linux-apache-mysql-php-lamp-stack-on-centos-7

yum install mariadb-server mariadb
sudo systemctl start mariadb
sudo mysql_secure_installation
sudo systemctl enable mariadb.service

say yes to all options in the console wizard during secure install

6.
Install JIRA
mysql -u root -p CREATE DATABASE jiradb CHARACTER SET utf8 COLLATE utf8_bin; GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, CREATE, DROP, ALTER, INDEX on jiradb.* TO 'jirauser'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'apollod0g!’ ; FLUSH PRIVILEGES; QUIT
* be sure to change to the password of your choice
cd /tmp/ ./atlassian-jira-6.3.13-x64.bin * Accept all defaults (standard settings, port 8080, etc.)
**************************************** IF YOU GET A JAVA HEAP ERROR ****************************************
If you get a Java Heap error when the service tries to start, modify the JVM settings:
vi /opt/atlassian/jira/bin/setenv.sh
Arrow down and set the following: JVM_MINIMUM_MEMORY="128m" JVM_MAXIMUM_MEMORY="256m"
Press Shift+Z twice
Then start the Jira service:
service jira start
**************************************
cd mysql-connector-java-5.1.34
cp *.jar /opt/atlassian/jira/lib/
service jira stop
service jira start


7.
Redirect port 8080 to port 80
I SKIPPED THIS STEP!
iptables -A PREROUTING -t nat -i eth0 -p tcp --dport 80 -j REDIRECT --to-port 8080


8.
Visit your new JIRA installation
Open a web browser and go to http://<the_ip_of_your_vps>; to configure JIRA.
Database type: MySQL Database host: localhost Database user: jirauser Database user password: <your password> Database: jiradb

I made the changes found here to the JIRA setenv file
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11788593/getting-jira-to-run-on-amazon-ec2-t1-micro-instance

Than I added 2 GB of swap to the server by following THIS digital ocean tutorial
https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-add-swap-on-centos-7
I left swampiness and cache pressure as defaults for now
